  "prompt": "What does it mean when ETA case number shows \"Certified\" in iCERT?",
  "response": "When an ETA (Employment and Training Administration) case number shows \"Certified\" in iCERT (the online system used for processing certain labor applications), it typically means that the Labor Condition Application (LCA) for a foreign worker has been approved and certified by the U.S. Department of Labor. \n\nFor H-1B, H-1B1, and E-3 visa applications, this \"Certified\" status indicates that:\n\n1. The employer has met the required labor conditions and attestations\n2. The application has been reviewed and accepted by the Department of Labor\n3. The LCA is now valid and can be used in the next steps of the visa application process\n\nThis certification is an important preliminary step before filing a visa petition with USCIS, showing that the employer has committed to certain wage and working condition requirements for the foreign worker.",
